        </figure>
        <figure id="f0401802" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g0401802" filename="../figg04/G0401802.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="272px" resolution="72"/>
            <caption>Figure 2. Hat Shaped Rotor</caption>
        </figure>
        <para>Antilock Brake System (ABS) braking systems use a "Hat Shaped" rotor with an exciter ring (
            <hotlnk xrefid="f0401803">Figure 3
                <xref refid="f0401803"/>
            </hotlnk>
            ). The exciter ring has one hundred teeth cast and machined as an integral part of "Hat-Shaped" rotors. The
            teeth excite a signal in the sensor as the rotor rotates which is provided to the ABS Electronic Control
            Unit. Damage to these teeth can affect the operation of the ABS system.
        </para>
        <figure id="f0401803" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g0401803" filename="../figg04/G0401803.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="272px" resolution="72"/>
            <caption>Figure 3. Rotor with Exciter Ring</caption>
        </figure>
    </svcproc>
